<br>
Using your scenarios-- a guy gets laid off from his job of 20 years, he's pissed off royaly and he's ready to act on his aggression.  Suddenly drug_buddy_01 comes in with an 8-ball and a QP of some killer bud, they sit at home, get totally trashed and jobless_loon_01 forgets all about his aggression.  The point is, anything can act as a catalyst for crime, be it drug addiction, mental illness, bad luck, or just poor judgement.<br>
<br>
We would save so much money if we were to legalize drugs.  Last time I checked the War on Drugs smoked up more tax dollars than I did pot.  Housing drug offenders in prison facilities isn't exactly free either.  Also you can't tax illegal substances sales transactions ( unless you're these <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.ksrevenue.org/perstaxtypesdrug.htm">retarded motherfuckers</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> ).  <br>
<br>
Instead of drugs taxing us, we could let the state regulate and tax them, much like they do alcohol now.  Drugs aren't going to go away, no matter how much we spend trying to make them.  So why not give responsible users the freedom to choose what they want to do, tax the sellers, and spend that money on drug prevention and other legitimate causes rather than incarcerating billy for his 8ball of coke. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=linale>Linale</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 296<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/30/03 12:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=113.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So why not give responsible users the freedom to choose <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
