You do realize that legal marijuana would easily cost less than cigarettes and alcohol to produce, and that coke will probably be right on par, right?<br>
<br>
The cost of production in most drugs is VERY VERY low, the cost of the product itself is so high due to the risks and hand-changes involved in transport and distribution.  <br>
<br>
The availability of these drugs will highly reduce crime, not increase it, and it would be a tremendous boost to the inner city and ghetto children to grow up without seeing the sale of drugs as a viable means of income.  Currently a person selling bud or crack can make a better income with a small amount of connections than they could working their ass off for 50 hours a week at McDonalds.  <br>
<br>
When people lose drugs as a source of income, initially you may have some increase in crime but with time people are going to migrate.  I've never personally known a drug distributor that's been involved in violence, although the people I've known were never into hardcore drug sales either, it was more of a way of extra cash on the side. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=treeslover>Treeslover</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1543<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/30/03 12:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=113.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Hahah I have new respect for the state in which I live.  Fucking ballsy to tax illegal things.. I wonder if they tax prostitution.<br>
