<br>
Recently they've done a study with self-injectors of THC which is the active ingredient, that showed it to be physically addictive.  The thing is, back in the 60's marijuana was about 1% THC, nowadays due to advances, the THC component is getting closer to 15%.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It might be considered mentally addictive, that's still up for debate.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The fact that it is mentally addictive has been fairly well established and accepted by all who have studied marijuana.  For the average user who smokes a joint or two every so often, you'll never see this because your body does not become acclimated to the drug, but the heavy users pretty much all consistently become mentally addicted to THC.<br>
<br>
Personally, I've tried coke, speed, and marijuana and I never became addicted to any of them.  My brother on the other hand became fully addicted to Cocaine.  He started out with Marijuana and then switched to Cocaine when the Marijuana no longer gave him that &quot;buzz&quot; after his system became immune to the THC component.  This isn't a terribly uncommon progression, and I assure you the cocaine fucked him up beyond words. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=204898">Ayiar Frullaniaceae</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
